statement:
Compute the following integrals. (Leave your answers in terms of $e$ or
$\ln()$.)

\begin{align*}I = \int_0^1 \frac{x}{(2-x)(1+2x)}\,dx\end{align*}

sols:
We proceed by partial fractions. Let A and B be constants such that

\begin{align*}\frac{x}{(2-x)(1 + 2x)} = \frac{A}{2-x} + \frac{B}{1 + 2x} = \frac{A(1+2x) + B(2-x)}{(2-x)(1 + 2x)}\end{align*}

Since the denominators are the same, the numerators must be equal and
hence

\begin{align*}\displaystyle x = A(1+2x) + B(2-x)\end{align*}

Now, since this equality holds for all values of x, we can plug in
specific values for x to get the coefficients. At $x=2$, we have

\begin{align*}\displaystyle 2 = A(1 + 2(2)) + B(2-(2)) = 5A\end{align*}

and so $A = \tfrac{2}{5}$. At $x = -\tfrac{1}{2}$, we have

\begin{align*}-\tfrac{1}{2} = A(1 + 2(-\tfrac{1}{2})) + B(2-(-\tfrac{1}{2})) = \tfrac{5}{2}B\end{align*}

and so $B = \tfrac{-1}{5}$. Hence, we have

\begin{align*}
&\int_{0}^{1} \frac{x}{(2-x)(1 + 2x)}\,dx\\
&= \int_{0}^{1} \frac{\tfrac{2}{5}}{2-x}\,dx + \int_{0}^{1} \frac{\tfrac{-1}{5}}{1 + 2x}\,dx \\
&= \left.\left(\frac25 \ln|2-x|(-1) - \frac15\ln|1 + 2x|\frac12\right)\right|_{0}^{1} \\
&= \left.\left(\frac{-2}{5}\ln|2-x| - \frac{1}{10}\ln|1 + 2x|\right)\right|_{0}^{1}\\
&= \frac{-2}{5}\ln|2-1| - \frac{1}{10}\ln|1 + 2(1)| - \frac{-2}{5}\ln|2-0| - \frac{1}{10}\ln|1 + 2(0)|\\
&= - \frac{1}{10}\ln|3| - \frac{-2}{5}\ln|2|\\
&= - \frac{\ln(3)}{10} + \frac{2\ln(2)}{5}\end{align*}
